<li id="cite_note-15">
<span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="IBM_PC#cite_ref-15">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">IBM did not offer own brand cassette recorders, but the 5150 had a cassette player jack, and IBM anticipated that entry level home users would connect their own <a href="http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compact_Cassette#Data_recording" title="Compact Cassette">cassette recorders for data storage</a> instead of using the more expensive <a href="http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floppy_drive" title="Floppy drive" class="mw-redirect">floppy drives</a> (and use their existing <a href="http://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/TV_set" title="TV set" class="mw-redirect">TV sets</a> as monitors); to this end, IBM initially offered the 5150 in a basic configuration without any floppy drives or monitor at the price of $1,565, whereas they offered a system with a monitor and single floppy drive for an initial $3,005. Few if any users however bought IBM 5150 PCs without floppy drives.</span>
