</li>
<li id="cite_note-36">
<span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="IBM_PC#cite_ref-36">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">327,680 bytes, i.e. 512 bytes × 8 sectors × 40 tracks × 2 sides</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-37">
<span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="IBM_PC#cite_ref-37">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">184,320 bytes, i.e. 512 bytes × 9 sectors × 40 tracks on the one side used</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-38">
<span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="IBM_PC#cite_ref-38">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">368,640 bytes, i.e. 512 bytes × 9 sectors × 40 tracks × 2 sides</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-39">
<span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="IBM_PC#cite_ref-39">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">However, IBM later offered the 5161 Expansion Unit, which could allow the installation of additional floppies, though this was not a typical configuration as the Expansion Unit shipped with one or two hard drives occupying the available drive bays.</span>
</li>
<li id="cite_note-40">
<span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="IBM_PC#cite_ref-40">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><a rel="nofollow" class="external free" href="http://www.pcworld.com/article/237878/can_you_do_real_work_with_the_30yearold_ibm_5150.html">http://www.pcworld.com/article/237878/can_you_do_real_work_with_the_30yearold_ibm_5150.html</a></span>
</li>
</ol>
</div>
